column18: A case report of a 30 year old young female who presented with hypertension and was subsequently diagnosed to have VHL disease with a c.293A>C mutation in the VHL gene, causing the substitution of Tyr with Ser at amino acid 98. Patient presented with adrenal pheochromocytoma, pancreatic mass, and cerebellar haemangioblastoma. Family history is unavailable. ACMG: PP2, PP4

column18: This abstract presented a case of a 37Y F with pheochromocytoma. Family history was significant for 1 sister who died just after delivery from severe hypertensive crisis, and a 26Y niece with left adrenal tumor and pancreatic tumor. Genetic sequencing revealed Q164R (c.491A<G) mutation in the patient and her still assymptomatic 5Y daughter. ACMG: 'PP4' because the patients' phenotypes and family history are highly specidic for a disease with single genetic etiology.

column18: This study examined the expression of hypoxia related genes in renal cell carcinoma. The authors analysed the tumor and surrounding healthy tissue in 10 patients who had radical nephrectomy because of RCC. DNA was isolated from blood, tumor and surrounding healthy tissue for sequencing VHL gene. Only 1 patient had a hereditary form of RCC with a substitution of leucine to proline at position 25 (P25L) as a polymorphism of the VHL gene. ACMG: 'PP4' because the patient' phenotype is highly specidic for a disease with single genetic etiology.

column18: This paper presented 2 cases of VHL syndrome presented simultaneously in twins. Molecular studies were performed for all subjects of the family. DNA was extracted from peripheral blood. Mutation was detected though southern vlotting hybridization to radiolabelled VHLcDNA (g7 probe). DNA changes in VHL were only detected in the twins, suggesting a de novo missence mutation in the exon 1B of VHL gene N78S (c.233A>G) (This mutation was labelled as a/G transition at codon 446 in the paper.) Case 1 (III.2) was a 16Y M who presented with right cerebellar hemangioblastoma, medullary and spinal cord solid tumors. Case 2 (III.3) was a 16Y M who presented with right cerebellar hemagioblastoma and nasal pharygeal bleeding fibroangioma. ACMG: 'PP4' because the patients' phenotypes is highly specidic for a disease with single genetic etiology.

column18: This paper presented a clinical case of a familial bilateral pheochromocytoma as a sole feature of the VHL disease type 2C. This is the first family with this disorder described in Bulgaria. Genetic analysis revealed a c.499C>T(p.Arg167Trp) missence mutation in exon 3 of VHL-gene. II1 (born 1974) and II3 (born 1977) are brothers who developed bilateral pheochromocytoma, I1 (born 1952), mother of the brothers, and III1 (born 2003), daughter of II1, are identified as carrier of this mutation. The original article is in foreign language. Data abstracted are from the English abstract and Figure 1. ACMG: 'PP1' because brothers II1, II3 who are confirmed carriers of the mutation in the family were both affected by VHL disease; 'PP4' because the patients' phenotypes and family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology.

column17: Three of his eight siblings tested positive for the 384delT mutation. His father had died as a complication of metastatic renal carcinoma; paper name :Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus and Von Hipple Lindau Syndrome- Sweet Presentation of a Bitter Disease
column18: A 19-year-old Saudi male presented to the emergency department with one-week history of polyuria and polydipsia and persistent was diagnosed with type I diabetes mellitus and treated for diabetic ketoacidosis. Abdominal pain persisted, and investigation revealed left sided pheochromocytoma, multiple cystic lesions in the pancreas, and bilateral renal clear cell carcinoma Furham grade I. Genetic testing confirmed 384delT frame-shift mutation in exon 2 of the VHL gene. Mutation was confirmed in 3 of 8 of the patient's sibilings, although phenotypic information on sibilings was not available. Patient's father died due to complications from metastatic renal carcinoma but genotypic information is unknown. ACMG: PVS1, PP1, PP4

column18: One family was found to carry both a heterozygous c.598C>T (p.Arg200Trp) mutation and a heterozygous c.482G>A (p.Arg161Gln) mutation. The family presented with pheochromocytoma, hemangioblastoma, renal cell carcinoma and erythrocytosis. ACMG: PP2, PP1, PP4

column18: A 17 year old female presented with high blood pressure and bilateral pheochromocytoma. Patient's father had bilateral pheochromocytoma at age 13, and two of the patient's sibilings also presente with bilateral pheochromocytoma. Anaylsis of germline variants revealed that a synonymous mutation c.342T>C was present in the patient and all three affected family members. Two unaffected family members did not have the mutation. Investigators hypothesize that since the mutation occurs 2 nucleotides into exon 2 it may have effects on VHL gene splicing. The patient's grandfather died of unknown renal disease at age 50. A germline mutation in the FH gene (c.556-4A>G) was also found in the patient, but not in any other family members. ACMG: PP4

column18: A 29Y women presented in the outpatient department of Xuanwu Hospital with 1-year history of amenorrhea and was found to have a brainstem hemangioblastoma, posterior fossa meningiomas and a pituitary spaceoccupying lesion causing hyperprolactinemia. Genetic analysis revealed a partial delection of exon 1 in the VHL gene. The patient had a negative family history for VHL mutations, suggesting a de novo mutation. ACMG: PVS1, PP4

column18: This abstract reported the case of unilateral single familial pheochromocytoma diagosed in a father and his son. They both carried a single mutation in the VHL gene, c.235C>G (p.R79G). The son was diagnosed and treated at age 9, while the father was intervened at age 40. ACMG: 'PP4' because the patients' phenotypes and family history are highly specidic for a disease with single genetic etiology.

column18: Thai male was diagnosed with VHL at age 20 when he was found to have a cerebellar hemangioblastoma. Genetic testing revealed a large deletion of exon 3 and poly A sites of VHL gene. 10 years later he was diagnosed with malignant pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor (PNET) with liver metastasis. ACMG: PVS1, PP4

A case report showed that a 24Y female was found with bilateral pheochromocytoma and a germline mutation c.500G>A (p.Arg167Gln) in the VHL gene. The mutation was confirmed in her mother who suffered from bilateral blindness for 20 years. No other pheotypic information of the mother was mentioned. ACMG: PM1, PP1, PP4

column18: Members of a Chinese multigeneration family underwent surgical therapy for renal tumors in Nanjing Drum tower hospital. 2 of the 4 members (mother and son) were diagnosed with VHL disease with a9kb deletion in exon 3 of the VHL gene. Grandfather had no history of disease and grandmother's history was unknown. Mother had CNS hemangioblastoma at age 33, retinal angioma at age 45, right ccrenal cell carcinoma and multiple pancreatic cysts at age 47. The son presented with CNS Hemangioblastoma at age 9, bilateral ccrenal cell carcinoma at age 27, pheochromocytoma at age 26 and papillary cystadenoma of the epididymis at age 24. ACMG: PVS1, PP1, PP4

column18: An 11-year-old boy with a 2-week history of nausea and vomiting was found with HP:0002666. Two years later he also developed HP:0002668. The patient is now 17Y old and had no other VHL disease manifestations. Genetic testing found a c.250G>A mutation in the VHL gene. His father and paternal aunt had histories of HP:0002666 but genetic testing for family members was not described. ACMG PP4
